<br>
Before level 5, before you choose your final class, each base class has 2 spell paths.  For example in Albion, the Elementalist has Path of Earth and Path of Ice.<br>
<br>
For each level there are spells in all paths that you can get.  These are basic damage, snare, etc. spells.<br>
<br>
Once you choose your final class, you will receive another path that you can use and spec in.  The Elementalist that becomes a Wizard gains the Path of Fire, for example.<br>
<br>
When you spec, you gain more power in the basic spells for the types, but also receive special spec type spells. The aformentioned Wizard can gain spells in Calefaction (earth spec), Liquifaction (ice spec) and Pyromancy (fire spec).  The spells in these paths are gained based on the skill points put into them.  I.e. if you put 5 spec points in Fire, you will gain the spells up to 5th in Pyromancy.  But if you were level 7, you would have up to 7th in Earth, Ice, &amp; Fire.<br>
<br>
As I mentioned, the more you spec in a type, the better you are in it.  So if you fully spec Fire, your ice &amp; earth spells will not improve (more damage, less power used, faster casting (I think)).  This is a reason to be sure what you want to spec in, and not just spread the points evenly -- you'll lose out at the high levels in damage, or buffs, or debuffs, or whatever you could've fully spec'ed.<br>
<br>
I hope this explains it enough for you.<br>
<br>
